VALUES
(1, 29, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'It is better that I give her to thee', 16, 52, 'question', 'Value of Choices', 'What does Laban''s reasoning reveal about the value of choices in relationships? How does the concept of ''better'' inform our understanding of prioritizing commitments in our lives today?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'than that I should give her to another man', 54, 96, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Another Man''', 'ἄλλος (allos, G243) - another, other. This term indicates an alternative or different choice. In this context, it emphasizes Laban''s preference for keeping Rachel within the family rather than allowing her to be married off to someone else, underscoring the significance of loyalty and ownership in familial relations.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G243", "description": "Strong''s number for ''another'' showing its significance in relational context."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'served seven years for Rachel', 10, 39, 'connection', 'Service and Sacrifice', 'Jacob''s commitment to serve seven years for Rachel parallels the New Testament concept of sacrificial love. In Ephesians 5:25, husbands are called to love their wives as Christ loved the church, emphasizing the depth of commitment involved. This connection highlights that true love often requires sacrifice and patience.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Ephesians 5:25", "description": "Husbands, love your wives, just as Christ loved the church and gave himself up for her."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'they seemed unto him but a few days', 45, 80, 'question', 'Perspective on Time', 'What does it reveal about Jacob''s character that seven years felt like only a few days due to his love for Rachel? How can we cultivate a similar perspective in our lives, focusing on love and joy rather than the burdens of time?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'for the love he had to her', 82, 108, 'theology', 'Love as a Driving Force', 'This verse suggests that love is a transformative force that can alter our experience of time and hardship. Many scholars believe this reflects a deeper biblical understanding of love, as seen in 1 Corinthians 13:4-7, where love is described as patient and kind. This passage invites us to reflect on how love influences our actions and relationships.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Corinthians 13:4-7", "description": "Love is patient, love is kind. It does not envy, it does not boast, it is not proud."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'for Rachel', 29, 39, 'greek', 'Significance of Names', 'רָחֵל (Rachel, H7354) - ewe, female sheep. Rachel''s name signifies tenderness and beauty, symbolizing the cherished qualities that Jacob values in her. This emphasizes the importance of names in biblical narratives, often reflecting character traits or destinies.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7354", "description": "Strong''s number for Rachel"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'Give me my wife, for my days are fulfilled, that I may go in unto her.', 27, 97, 'connection', 'Fulfillment of Service', 'This phrase resonates with the theme of fulfilled commitment seen in Exodus 21:3, where a servant''s time of service is clearly defined. Just as Jacob''s seven years of labor for Rachel come to completion, the biblical narrative often emphasizes the importance of fulfilling one''s promises and obligations, reflecting the covenantal nature of relationships in Scripture.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 21:3", "description": "Both verses highlight the completion of a predetermined period of service."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'for my days are fulfilled', 44, 69, 'theology', 'Covenantal Promises', 'Many scholars believe that Jacob''s statement reflects the broader biblical theme of covenantal fulfillment. The completion of his service for Rachel can be seen as a foreshadowing of God''s faithfulness to His promises. This passage invites readers to consider how God honors commitments and how believers are called to emulate such faithfulness in their own lives.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the importance of fulfilling one''s obligations as a reflection of God''s faithfulness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'Give me my wife', 27, 42, 'question', 'Desire and Relationship', 'What does Jacob''s urgent request reveal about the nature of desire in relationships? How might this reflect God''s design for marital commitment and intimacy? Consider how Jacob''s longing for Rachel can prompt reflection on the importance of pursuing meaningful connections in our own lives.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'that I may go in unto her.', 71, 97, 'greek', 'Biblical Intimacy', 'בָּא (bo, H935) - to enter, come in. This Hebrew word emphasizes the physical and relational intimacy that is a key aspect of marriage. Jacob''s desire to ''go in unto her'' signifies the deep connection intended in the marriage covenant, highlighting the significance of both emotional and physical unity in biblical relationships.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H935", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term used in the context of entering into a relationship."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'Laban gathered together all the men of the place, and made a feast.', 4, 71, 'connection', 'Cultural Significance of Feasts', 'The act of gathering for a feast in this context resonates with the communal celebrations seen throughout Scripture. For instance, in Exodus 12:14, the Passover is established as a feast to remember God''s deliverance. This highlights the importance of community and shared experiences in marking significant life events. Laban''s feast signifies not only a wedding celebration but also the cultural value placed on community in covenant relationships.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 12:14", "description": "The Passover feast as a communal celebration."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'made a feast.', 58, 71, 'theology', 'Theology of Celebration', 'This passage suggests a theological understanding of celebration within God’s covenant community. Many scholars believe that feasts serve as reminders of God’s provision and presence, fostering unity among His people. Celebrations in biblical contexts often point to deeper spiritual truths, such as rejoicing in God’s faithfulness and the importance of community worship.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'gathered together all the men of the place', 10, 52, 'question', 'Community and Relationships', 'What does this gathering of the community reveal about the importance of relationships in our spiritual journey? How might our own celebrations reflect the communal aspect of faith in our lives?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'Laban gathered together', 4, 27, 'greek', 'Gathering and Assembly', 'קָבַץ (qabats, H6908) - to gather, assemble, or collect. This Hebrew term emphasizes the act of coming together, reflecting communal unity and shared purpose, which is foundational in biblical narratives surrounding covenant relationships.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H6908", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term related to gathering."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'And it came to pass in the evening, that he took Leah his daughter, and brought her to him; and he went in unto her.', 0, 116, 'connection', 'Deception and Relationships', 'This incident draws parallels with other biblical accounts of deception in relationships, particularly with Jacob''s own past actions in deceiving his father Isaac (Genesis 27:18-29). The theme of deception highlights the consequences of one''s actions and choices in familial bonds, serving as a reminder of how one''s past can return in unexpected ways.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 27:18-29", "description": "Jacob deceives Isaac to receive the blessing meant for Esau."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'And it came to pass in the evening, that he took Leah his daughter, and brought her to him; and he went in unto her.', 0, 116, 'theology', 'God''s Sovereignty in Relationships', 'Many scholars believe this passage illustrates God''s sovereignty over human affairs, even in instances of manipulation and deceit. Leah''s being chosen in place of Rachel may reflect God''s purposes at work, showing how He can use complex human situations to fulfill His divine plans, as seen in the later significance of Leah''s children in Israel''s history.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses God''s sovereignty in human relationships and events."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'And it came to pass in the evening, that he took Leah his daughter, and brought her to him; and he went in unto her.', 0, 116, 'question', 'Understanding Divine Timing', 'What does the timing of this event, occurring ''in the evening,'' suggest about God''s timing in our own lives? How does this parallel with the idea that God often works in ways that may not align with our expectations?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'And it came to pass in the evening, that he took Leah his daughter, and brought her to him; and he went in unto her.', 0, 116, 'greek', 'Understanding ''went in unto her''', 'בָּא (bo, H935) - to enter, come in. This term emphasizes the intimate nature of the relationship being formed. It is significant as it denotes the consummation of marriage, which is a sacred union in biblical texts. Understanding this term helps to grasp the weight of the actions taken in this passage.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H935", "description": "Strong''s number for ''to enter, come in.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'Zilpah his maid for an handmaid', 38, 69, 'connection', 'Maidservants in Scripture', 'The mention of Zilpah as Leah''s maidservant connects to other instances in Scripture where maidservants play significant roles. For example, in Genesis 16:1, Sarai gives Hagar to Abram to bear a child, illustrating the cultural practice of using maidservants in family lineage matters. This connection underscores the societal norms surrounding inheritance and family structure in ancient times.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 16:1", "description": "Sarai''s use of Hagar as a maidservant to bear a child."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'Zilpah his maid for an handmaid', 38, 69, 'theology', 'Role of Handmaids', 'This passage suggests the theological implications of familial roles and God''s sovereignty in human affairs. Many scholars believe that the inclusion of maidservants like Zilpah reflects God''s use of imperfect systems to fulfill His promises, as seen in the lineage of Israel. It raises questions about how God can work through human decisions and cultural practices to achieve His divine purposes.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'his maid for an handmaid', 45, 69, 'question', 'Understanding Handmaid Roles', 'What does the role of Zilpah as a handmaid reveal about the value of individuals within God''s plan? How might this inform our understanding of dignity and purpose in all people, regardless of their societal status?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'gave unto his daughter Leah', 10, 37, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Gave''', 'נָתַן (natan, H5414) - to give, put, set. This Hebrew term emphasizes the act of giving, which implies authority and intentionality in the relationship dynamics depicted in the narrative. Laban''s action of giving Leah along with her maid highlights the complexities of familial obligations and the value placed on women in this cultural context.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5414", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word ''natan''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'What is this thou hast done unto me?', 85, 121, 'question', 'Question of Justice', 'What does Jacob''s cry reveal about his understanding of justice and fairness in relationships? How might this moment reflect our own struggles with perceived injustice in our lives, especially when expectations are not met?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'did not I serve with thee for Rachel?', 122, 159, 'connection', 'Expectations and Deception', 'Jacob''s expectation of marrying Rachel after seven years of service highlights themes of commitment and deception. This parallels with Genesis 27:35, where deception in the family leads to significant consequences. Both instances show the complexities and consequences of human relationships.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 27:35", "description": "This verse showcases another instance of familial deception."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'wherefore then hast thou beguiled me?', 160, 197, 'theology', 'The Nature of Deception', 'This passage suggests that deception is a recurring theme in the narrative of Jacob''s life, reflecting the broader theological concept of the fallen nature of humanity. Many scholars believe that the story illustrates the consequences of deceit, not only in familial relationships but also in our relationship with God.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'behold, it was Leah:', 42, 62, 'greek', 'Seeing and Understanding', 'הִנֵּה (hinneh, H2009) - behold, look, here. This term often signifies a moment of revelation or realization, emphasizing the importance of perception in understanding one''s circumstances. Jacob''s realization is pivotal, as it marks a turning point in the narrative.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2009", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term ''hinneh''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'It must not be so done in our country,', 16, 54, 'connection', 'Cultural Norms in Scripture', 'The phrase highlights the importance of cultural customs and traditions in biblical narratives. For instance, the notion of the firstborn''s rights is echoed in Deuteronomy 21:17, which emphasizes the duty to recognize the firstborn''s inheritance. This connection illustrates how cultural practices can influence personal relationships and decisions, shaping the narrative of God''s people.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Deuteronomy 21:17", "description": "Discusses the rights of the firstborn in Israelite law."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'the younger before the firstborn.', 63, 96, 'theology', 'Divine Order and Priority', 'This passage suggests a theological principle regarding divine order and priority, which many scholars believe reflects God''s choice of the unlikely or the unexpected for His purposes, as seen in the stories of Isaac over Ishmael and Jacob over Esau. The preference for the younger can be seen as a foreshadowing of God''s grace that operates outside human expectations.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses God''s sovereign choices in biblical narratives."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'It must not be so done in our country,', 16, 54, 'question', 'Challenging Cultural Norms', 'How do cultural norms shape our understanding of right and wrong? In what ways might we be called to challenge or uphold these norms in our own lives, particularly when they conflict with God''s principles as revealed in Scripture?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'the younger before the firstborn.', 63, 96, 'greek', 'Firstborn Significance', 'בְּכוֹר (bĕkhor, H1060) - firstborn, eldest son. This term emphasizes the special status and rights that the firstborn held in ancient Israelite culture, including inheritance and leadership roles, which is central to understanding the tension in Jacob''s story.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1060", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word meaning ''firstborn.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'Fulfil her week, and we will give thee this also for the service which thou shalt serve with me yet seven other years.', 0, 118, 'connection', 'Cultural Context of Marriage', 'This verse highlights the cultural practice of fulfilling a week of wedding festivities, which is significant in understanding ancient Near Eastern customs. Similar practices are noted in other cultures, such as in Exodus 22:16-17, where the bride price is discussed. Understanding these customs provides insight into the social and familial dynamics of Jacob''s time. It also underscores the value placed on women and marriage in these societies.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 22:16", "description": "Context of marriage customs and bride price"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'for the service which thou shalt serve with me yet seven other years.', 49, 118, 'theology', 'Service and Commitment', 'This passage illustrates the theme of servitude and commitment within biblical narratives. Many scholars believe it reflects God’s covenantal relationship with His people, where commitment and service are foundational. Jacob’s willingness to serve another seven years for Rachel demonstrates the idea of sacrificial love, echoing themes seen in the New Testament concerning Christ''s sacrifice for the Church.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discussion on commitment and love in Scripture"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'Fulfil her week, and we will give thee this also', 0, 48, 'question', 'Understanding Fulfillment', 'What does it mean to ''fulfil her week'' in the context of commitment and cultural expectations? How does this concept of fulfilling obligations reflect on our own commitments in relationships and spiritual life today? Can we see parallels in our own lives where we are called to fulfill certain commitments or responsibilities?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'And Jacob did so, and fulfilled her week:', 0, 41, 'connection', 'Fulfillment of Commitment', 'Jacob''s fulfillment of Leah''s week reflects a deep commitment to his obligations. This resonates with the New Testament''s call for faithfulness in commitments, as seen in Matthew 5:37, where believers are encouraged to let their ''yes'' be ''yes'' and ''no'' be ''no.'' The connection emphasizes the importance of integrity in relationships.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 5:37", "description": "Encouragement for integrity in commitments."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'and he gave him Rachel his daughter to wife also.', 42, 91, 'theology', 'Divine Providence in Marriage', 'This passage suggests that God’s providence orchestrates relationships and marriages, as seen throughout Scripture. Many scholars believe that the complexities of Jacob''s marriages serve to illustrate God''s sovereignty in human affairs, reflecting the broader biblical theme of divine providence.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Genesis 29:1-30", "description": "Discussion on God''s providence in Jacob''s life."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'fulfilled her week:', 22, 41, 'greek', 'Hebrew Term for Fulfillment', 'שָׁבוּעַ (shabuwa'', H7620) - week, a period of seven days. This term indicates not only the time frame Jacob adhered to but also symbolizes the completion of a commitment and cycle, reflecting the importance of time in fulfilling promises.', 'character.book.closed', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7620", "description": "Hebrew word for week."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'And Jacob did so,', 0, 17, 'question', 'What Drives Our Actions?', 'What motivates Jacob''s decision to fulfill the week? This prompts reflection on our own motivations in fulfilling commitments. Are we driven by obligation, love, or a desire for approval? Exploring this can lead to a deeper understanding of our own relationships and decisions.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 29, 29, 'kjv', 'Bilhah his handmaid', 38, 57, 'connection', 'Significance of Handmaids', 'The mention of Bilhah as Rachel''s handmaid echoes in Genesis 30:3, where Rachel offers Bilhah to Jacob to bear children on her behalf. This reflects cultural practices of the time regarding marriage and childbearing, emphasizing the importance of lineage. The connection highlights the role of women in the biblical narrative, often navigating complex social dynamics to fulfill family and cultural expectations.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 30:3", "description": "Rachel''s use of Bilhah as a surrogate"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 29, 29, 'kjv', 'Laban gave to Rachel', 4, 24, 'theology', 'The Role of Gifts', 'This passage illustrates the significance of gifts and provisions in relationships, particularly in the context of marriage. Many scholars believe this reflects the biblical principle that God provides for His people, symbolized through familial gifts. It underscores the covenantal aspect of marriage, where both parties are expected to contribute to the well-being of one another.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary on the Whole Bible", "description": "Discussion on the significance of gifts in biblical marriages"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 29, 29, 'kjv', 'Bilhah his handmaid', 38, 57, 'greek', 'Role of Handmaids', 'In this context, the Hebrew word for ''handmaid'' is שִׁפְחָה (shiphchah, H8198) - a female servant or concubine. This term often signifies a lower social status but also reflects the responsibilities entrusted to them. The inclusion of Bilhah emphasizes the complex family structures and social hierarchies in ancient Israel.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8198", "description": "Strong''s definition of \u05e9\u05b4\u05c1\u05e4\u05b0\u05d7\u05b8\u05d4"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 29, 29, 'kjv', 'handmaid to be her maid', 49, 72, 'question', 'Understanding Servitude', 'What does it reveal about societal norms and personal identity when Rachel is given a maid? How might this shape our understanding of service and authority in relationships today? Reflecting on this can provide insight into how we view roles within our own communities and families.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 30, 30, 'kjv', 'loved also Rachel more than Leah', 40, 72, 'connection', 'Sibling Rivalry in Scripture', 'This phrase echoes the themes of familial favoritism seen in other biblical narratives, such as the relationship between Isaac and Rebekah (Genesis 25:28) where Isaac loved Esau more than Jacob. Such dynamics often lead to conflict and strife within families, highlighting the destructive nature of favoritism. Understanding these patterns can deepen our insight into the complex human relationships depicted in Scripture.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 25:28", "description": "Isaac''s favoritism towards Esau"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 30, 30, 'kjv', 'loved also Rachel more than Leah', 40, 72, 'theology', 'God''s Sovereignty in Relationships', 'This passage raises important theological questions about God''s sovereignty and human choice. Many scholars believe that the preference Jacob shows for Rachel over Leah illustrates the complexities of divine providence in human relationships. Despite Jacob''s favoritism, God''s plan unfolds through Leah''s subsequent fertility, demonstrating that God''s purposes often work through human imperfections and choices.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Insights on divine providence in family dynamics"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 30, 30, 'kjv', 'served with him yet seven other years', 78, 115, 'question', 'Value of Commitment', 'What does Jacob''s willingness to serve an additional seven years for Rachel reveal about the nature of love and commitment? How can this reflect our own commitments in relationships and our faith journey? In a world where instant gratification is often prioritized, what does this story teach us about perseverance and dedication?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 30, 30, 'kjv', 'And he went in also unto Rachel', 0, 31, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Went In''', 'בָּא (ba, H935) - to go in, enter. This Hebrew term signifies more than mere physical entry; it can imply intimate relationships and the covenantal aspect of marriage. The use of this term in the context of Jacob''s union with Rachel indicates the deepening of their relationship beyond mere affection, establishing a significant covenantal bond.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H935", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term used"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 31, 31, 'kjv', 'when the Lord saw that Leah was hated', 4, 41, 'connection', 'God''s Awareness of Affliction', 'This phrase echoes God''s attentiveness to His people''s suffering, seen in Exodus 3:7 where He declares, ''I have surely seen the affliction of my people.'' Both Scriptures highlight God''s compassion and intervention in human pain, suggesting that He is not distant but actively involved in our struggles.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 3:7", "description": "God''s acknowledgment of Israel''s suffering"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 31, 31, 'kjv', 'the Lord saw that Leah was hated', 9, 41, 'theology', 'Divine Justice and Compassion', 'Many scholars believe this verse illustrates the theological theme of divine justice, revealing that God responds to human injustices. Leah''s plight prompts God''s action, suggesting that He values the marginalized and oppressed, which aligns with the broader biblical narrative of His concern for justice.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discussion on God''s justice and compassion"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 31, 31, 'kjv', 'opened her womb: but Rachel was barren', 46, 84, 'greek', 'Understanding ''opened'' in Hebrew', 'פָּתַח (patach, H6605) - to open, to loosen. This term signifies not just the physical opening of Leah''s womb but can represent God''s granting of opportunity and favor, contrasting with Rachel''s barrenness, which symbolizes unfulfilled potential and desire.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H6605", "description": "Hebrew term for ''opened''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 31, 31, 'kjv', 'the Lord saw that Leah was hated', 9, 41, 'question', 'Reflecting on Divine Observance', 'What does it mean to you that God sees the suffering of those who feel rejected or unloved? How does this understanding shape your response to those who are marginalized in your community?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 29, 32, 32, 'kjv', 'Surely the Lord hath looked upon my affliction;', 82, 129, 'connection', 'God Sees Affliction', 'This phrase echoes the sentiment found in Exodus 3:7, where God declares, ''I have surely seen the affliction of my people.'' Both verses illustrate the compassionate nature of God, who is aware of human suffering and responds to it. This connection emphasizes God''s active involvement in the lives of His people.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 3:7", "description": "God''s promise to deliver His people from suffering."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');